sounds kind of embarrassing. Sometimes no matter how much time and energy you put into something,

153
00:07:15,729 --> 00:07:20,591
it's not going to be good just because video games. It's up to you to dig into your creative

154
00:07:20,631 --> 00:07:24,793
toolbox and tackle all the problems, expected and unexpected, that are thrown at you.

155
00:07:26,061 --> 00:07:28,182
You know, there's the age-old problems.

156
00:07:28,562 --> 00:07:30,583
Perhaps game design is at lockdown.

157
00:07:30,923 --> 00:07:32,904
Perhaps some big opportunity arose

158
00:07:32,944 --> 00:07:34,144
and you have to ship early.

159
00:07:34,785 --> 00:07:37,466
Or perhaps you just never even had enough time to begin with.

160
00:07:38,406 --> 00:07:40,507
And then there's the weirder problems.

161
00:07:41,087 --> 00:07:42,928
Perhaps all your animations are sped up

162
00:07:42,968 --> 00:07:45,789
to match the beat of a song out of your control.

163
00:07:46,529 --> 00:07:47,710
Or your animations are shared

164
00:07:47,750 --> 00:07:50,351
across totally wildly different characters.

165
00:07:51,242 --> 00:07:52,903
Or you can animate your character's body,

166
00:07:53,103 --> 00:07:55,945
but their heads are controlled by a avatared VR headset.

167
00:07:56,686 --> 00:07:58,207
All real things I've had to deal with.

168
00:07:58,847 --> 00:08:01,169
And no matter how normal or weird your problems are,

169
00:08:01,269 --> 00:08:02,970
things happen and you just have to get it done.

170
00:08:03,411 --> 00:08:04,972
Don't get me wrong, I'm not saying you should

171
00:08:04,992 --> 00:08:06,873
death march, crunch your way through it,

172
00:08:07,214 --> 00:08:08,775
but don't just give up and half-ass it.

173
00:08:08,935 --> 00:08:10,976
Work smart, not just hard.

174
00:08:11,717 --> 00:08:12,598
And real talk?

175
00:08:13,584 --> 00:08:17,047
Focus on what's important and work on the extras if you have time.

176
00:08:17,727 --> 00:08:21,690
Don't sacrifice your friends and family crunching on something that no one's going to notice but you.

177
00:08:22,491 --> 00:08:28,135
Because players are not going to care that you stayed late to put that subtle offset in your character's fingers.

178
00:08:28,815 --> 00:08:31,557
And that's who we're making these games for, the players.

179
00:08:32,118 --> 00:08:37,622
On one game I worked on, I decided it was better to add animation variety than to polish a few animations to a perfect.

180
00:08:38,975 --> 00:08:41,577
polish. I wanted the player to be delighted and surprised when

181
00:08:41,597 --> 00:08:44,299
their character did something fun and unexpected. Always

182
00:08:44,319 --> 00:08:47,601
remember who your game is for. And yes, that means for that

183
00:08:47,641 --> 00:08:50,683
game, I didn't end up with many demo reel pieces. But that

184
00:08:50,703 --> 00:08:53,465
doesn't mean the animation was bad. It accomplished what it

185
00:08:53,485 --> 00:08:56,588
needed to for the situation and the players enjoyed it. You're

186
00:08:56,608 --> 00:09:00,550
making a game, not a demo reel. And that's the point. Really

187
00:09:00,590 --> 00:09:04,333
think about what's right for the situation. Sometimes a small set

188
00:09:04,353 --> 00:09:06,335
of hyper polished animations is what you need.

189
00:09:06,845 --> 00:09:11,306
or maybe variety is key, and sometimes things are just a mess and you have to be flexible.

190
00:09:12,106 --> 00:09:15,927
And once you have decided on your direction, try to get animations in the game quickly.

191
00:09:16,547 --> 00:09:20,688
Test them, throw them out, and make new ones. This is especially true when the design is

192
00:09:20,748 --> 00:09:24,989
constantly changing. And don't spend time polishing something until you know things

193
00:09:25,069 --> 00:09:31,310
are working as a whole. Once everything is roughed in and working, make a polish priority list.

194
00:09:31,830 --> 00:09:36,251
Take the time to identify what animation is most important, even

195
00:09:37,074 --> 00:09:39,216
Ah, and hit polish for them first,

196
00:09:39,456 --> 00:09:40,837
even if they aren't your favorites.

197
00:09:41,497 --> 00:09:43,338
Don't get caught up in the little details

198
00:09:43,759 --> 00:09:45,119
and ignore the big picture.

199
00:09:46,300 --> 00:09:48,662
And the next thing to do is to work in passes.

200
00:09:50,063 --> 00:09:51,203
It gives you some leeway

201
00:09:51,844 --> 00:09:53,925
when your team pulls the rug out from under you.

202
00:09:54,606 --> 00:09:57,447
If you haven't focused on polishing animations one at a time,

203
00:09:58,401 --> 00:10:01,702
you won't lose as much work if someone cuts something or changes the design.

204
00:10:02,242 --> 00:10:05,683
